    "import os\n",
    "import os.path as osp\n",
    "import random as rand\n",
    "from pathlib import Path\n",
    "import shutil as sh\n",
    "\n",

    "from PIL import Image\n",
    "\n",
    "warnings.filterwarnings(\"ignore\")\n",
    "\n",

    "\n",

    "input_dir = Path(\"input\")\n",
    "outputs_dir = Path(\"_output\")\n",

    "\n",

    "we_md_windows_im = Image.open(media_dir / \"we_MD_windows.png\")\n",
    "continuation_runs_im = Image.open(media_dir / \"continuation_runs.png\")\n",
    "contig_tree_im = Image.open(media_dir / \"contig_tree.png\")\n",
    "CSN_workflow_shortway_im = Image.open(media_dir / \"CSN_workflow_shortway.png\")\n",
    "linking_files_im = Image.open(media_dir / \"linking_files.png\")"
   ]

   "source": [
    "## Running the simulation\n",
    "\n",
    "Here we run some simulations so that we can showcase combining them for analysis. Since this tutorial isn't about running simulations we won't discuss this part much.\n",
    "\n",
    "This first block is just to set up all the parameters and components for the simulation. We will be running multiple simulations with these and just change the reporters we are using."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "metadata": {
    "slideshow": {
     "slide_type": "skip"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import sys\n",
    "from copy import copy, deepcopy\n",
    "import os\n",
    "import os.path as osp\n",
    "import pickle\n",
    "\n",
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import scipy.spatial.distance as scidist\n",
    "\n",
    "import simtk.openmm.app as omma\n",
    "import simtk.openmm as omm\n",
    "import simtk.unit as unit\n",
    "\n",
    "from openmm_systems.test_systems import LennardJonesPair\n",
    "import mdtraj as mdj\n",
    "from wepy.util.mdtraj import mdtraj_to_json_topology\n",
    "\n",
    "from wepy.sim_manager import Manager\n",
    "\n",
    "from wepy.resampling.distances.distance import Distance\n",
    "from wepy.resampling.resamplers.wexplore import WExploreResampler\n",
    "from wepy.walker import Walker\n",
    "from wepy.runners.openmm import OpenMMRunner, OpenMMState\n",
    "from wepy.runners.openmm import UNIT_NAMES, GET_STATE_KWARG_DEFAULTS\n",
    "from wepy.work_mapper.mapper import Mapper\n",
    "from wepy.boundary_conditions.unbinding import UnbindingBC\n",
    "from wepy.reporter.hdf5 import WepyHDF5Reporter\n",
    "\n",
    "from wepy.hdf5 import WepyHDF5\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "## PARAMETERS\n",
    "\n",
    "# we use the Reference platform because this is just a test\n",
    "PLATFORM = 'Reference'\n",
    "\n",
    "# Langevin Integrator\n",
    "TEMPERATURE= 300.0*unit.kelvin\n",
    "FRICTION_COEFFICIENT = 1/unit.picosecond\n",
    "# step size of time integrations\n",
    "STEP_SIZE = 0.002*unit.picoseconds\n",
    "\n",
    "# Resampler parameters\n",
    "\n",
    "# the maximum weight allowed for a walker\n",
    "PMAX = 0.5\n",
    "# the minimum weight allowed for a walker\n",
    "PMIN = 1e-12\n",
    "\n",
    "# the maximum number of regions allowed under each parent region\n",
    "MAX_N_REGIONS = (10, 10, 10, 10)\n",
    "\n",
    "# the maximum size of regions, new regions will be created if a walker\n",
    "# is beyond this distance from each voronoi image unless there is an\n",
    "# already maximal number of regions\n",
    "MAX_REGION_SIZES = (1, 0.5, .35, .25) # nanometers\n",
    "\n",
    "# boundary condition parameters\n",
    "\n",
    "# maximum distance between between any atom of the ligand and any\n",
    "# other atom of the protein, if the shortest such atom-atom distance\n",
    "# is larger than this the ligand will be considered unbound and\n",
    "# restarted in the initial state\n",
    "CUTOFF_DISTANCE = 1.0 # nm\n",
    "\n",
    "# reporting parameters\n",
    "\n",
    "# these are the properties of the states (i.e. from OpenMM) which will\n",
    "# be saved into the HDF5\n",
    "SAVE_FIELDS = ('positions', 'box_vectors', 'velocities')\n",
    "\n",
    "# make a dictionary of units for adding to the HDF5\n",
    "units = dict(UNIT_NAMES)\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "## System\n",
    "\n",
    "# make the test system\n",
    "test_sys = LennardJonesPair()\n",
    "\n",
    "## Molecular Topology\n",
    "\n",
    "mdtraj_topology = mdj.Topology.from_openmm(test_sys.topology)\n",
    "\n",
    "json_str_top = mdtraj_to_json_topology(mdtraj_topology)\n",
    "\n",
    "## Runner\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "# make the integrator\n",
    "integrator = omm.LangevinIntegrator(TEMPERATURE, \n",
    "                                    FRICTION_COEFFICIENT,\n",
    "                                    STEP_SIZE)\n",
    "\n",
    "# make a context and set the positions\n",
    "context = omm.Context(test_sys.system, \n",
    "                      copy(integrator))\n",
    "context.setPositions(test_sys.positions)\n",
    "\n",
    "# get the data from this context so we have a state to start the\n",
    "# simulation with\n",
    "get_state_kwargs = dict(GET_STATE_KWARG_DEFAULTS)\n",
    "init_sim_state = context.getState(**get_state_kwargs)\n",
    "init_state = OpenMMState(init_sim_state)\n",
    "\n",
    "# initialize the runner\n",
    "runner = OpenMMRunner(test_sys.system, \n",
    "                      test_sys.topology, \n",
    "                      integrator, \n",
    "                      platform=PLATFORM)\n",
    "\n",
    "## Distance Metric\n",
    "# we define a simple distance metric for this system, assuming the\n",
    "# positions are in a 'positions' field\n",
    "class PairDistance(Distance):\n",
    "\n",
    "    def __init__(self, metric=scidist.euclidean):\n",
    "        self.metric = metric\n",
    "\n",
    "    def image(self, state):\n",
    "        return state['positions']\n",
    "\n",
    "    def image_distance(self, image_a, image_b):\n",
    "        dist_a = self.metric(image_a[0], image_a[1])\n",
    "        dist_b = self.metric(image_b[0], image_b[1])\n",
    "\n",
    "        return np.abs(dist_a - dist_b)\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "# make a distance object which can be used to compute the distance\n",
    "# between two walkers, for our scorer class\n",
    "distance = PairDistance()\n",
    "\n",
    "## Resampler\n",
    "resampler = WExploreResampler(distance=distance,\n",
    "                               init_state=init_state,\n",
    "                               max_region_sizes=MAX_REGION_SIZES,\n",
    "                               max_n_regions=MAX_N_REGIONS,\n",
    "                               pmin=PMIN, pmax=PMAX)\n",
    "\n",
    "## Boundary Conditions\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "# initialize the unbinding boundary conditions\n",
    "ubc = UnbindingBC(cutoff_distance=CUTOFF_DISTANCE,\n",
    "                  initial_state=init_state,\n",
    "                  topology=json_str_top,\n",
    "                  ligand_idxs=np.array(test_sys.ligand_indices),\n",
    "                  receptor_idxs=np.array(test_sys.receptor_indices))\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "## Work Mapper\n",
    "\n",
    "# a simple work mapper\n",
    "mapper = Mapper()\n",
    "\n",
    "## initial walkers\n",
    "n_walkers = 4\n",
    "init_weight = 1.0 / n_walkers\n",
    "init_walkers = [Walker(OpenMMState(init_sim_state), init_weight) for i in range(n_walkers)]\n",
    "\n",
    "## run parameters\n",
    "n_cycles = 100\n",
    "n_steps = 1000\n",
    "# steps for each cycle\n",
    "steps = [n_steps for i in range(n_cycles)]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "#### First Simulation\n",
    "\n",
    "Nothing fancy here, we just make a reporter that will generate the `WepyHDF5` file. We need to do `deepcopy` on all the components because we will be reusing this initial state for the other simulations and passing them by reference here will mutate them. The `Manager` won't do copies automatically for you as this may be expensive in some situations."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "run1_hdf5_reporter = WepyHDF5Reporter(\n",
    "    file_path=str(outputs_dir / \"results_run1.wepy.h5\"),\n",
    "                                 mode='w',\n",
    "                                 save_fields=SAVE_FIELDS,\n",
    "                                 resampler=resampler,\n",
    "                                 boundary_conditions=ubc,\n",
    "                                 topology=json_str_top,\n",
    "                                 units=units)\n",
    "\n",
    "sim_manager_1 = Manager(deepcopy(init_walkers),\n",
    "                        runner=deepcopy(runner),\n",
    "                        resampler=deepcopy(resampler),\n",
    "                        boundary_conditions=deepcopy(ubc),\n",
    "                        work_mapper=deepcopy(mapper),\n",
    "                        reporters=[run1_hdf5_reporter]\n",
    "                    )\n",
    "(run1_walkers, \n",
    " (run1_runner, run1_bc, run1_resampler)) = \\\n",
    "             sim_manager_1.run_simulation(n_cycles, steps)\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "#### Second Simulation\n",
    "\n",
    "Same as the first one but we just want a separate dataset so we can demonstrate how to aggregate independently generated datasets later."
   ]
  },

    "                                 save_fields=SAVE_FIELDS,\n",

    "                                 boundary_conditions=ubc,\n",

    "\n",
    "# run two simulations from the initial conditions\n",
    "sim_manager_2 = Manager(deepcopy(init_walkers),\n",

    "                    )\n",
    "(run2_walkers, \n",

   ]
  },

   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",

   },
   "source": [
    "### Analysis Workflow\n",
    "\n",
    "Now that we have generated all of our simulation data we can start analyzing it.\n",
    "\n",
    "We will start with a workflow something like this, where on one branch (green) we want to do some dimensionally reduction and cluster the states we collected into \"macrostates\".\n",
    "\n",
    "On the other branch (blue, red, purple) we will do the necessary bookkeeping to get the walker family tree taking into account both the cloning & merging as well as any walkers that have warped through boundary conditions.\n",
    "\n",
    "In the end we can combine these states with the walker family tree to calculate the transition probabilities between those macrostates. This end result is something similar to a Markov State Model (MSM) which we call a Conformation State Model (CSN). The distinction merely refers to some rather rigorous requirements a true Markov State Model must have that we aren't directly attempting to verify here."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 6,
   "metadata": {
    "slideshow": {
     "slide_type": "slide"
    }
   },

     "data": {

      "text/plain": [
       "<PIL.Image.Image image mode=RGB size=733x507 at 0x7F77B40E28D0>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 6,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "rescale(CSN_workflow_longway_im, 1.0)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "#### Calculating Observables\n",
    "\n",
    "In order to do the macrostate clustering we need to calculate some interesting observables over the state data. You could use absolute positions of the particles or the energies or something that is calculated on-the-fly by the simulations but we want to showcase how to do this yourself. For a real molecular system this might be the solvent accessible surface area or the radius of gyration.\n",
    "\n",
    "Because our example is very simple (just two particles) there isn't much we can do. So we'll just calculate the Euclidean distance between the two particles. Not coincidentally, this is also the distance metric we used. We are actually using this distance for a similar purpose (clustering) except while the resampler (WExplore) was doing this \"on-the-fly\" we have all of the simulation data at once and so will likely get better boundaries between clusters than our resampler.\n",
    "\n",
    "To do this we have to define a function `pair_dist_obs` of a particular form that we can then pass to the `WepyHDF5.compute_observable` function which maps it over the data. Since this is a small simulation with small molecules we can do it in memory in a single process. Real simulation data can be much larger, for this you are free to implement your own computational strategies using a lower level API or you can see if the methods in the `wepy.analysis.distributed` module are suitable, which uses the distributed computing framework `dask`."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 7,
   "metadata": {
    "slideshow": {
     "slide_type": "-"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def pair_dist_obs(fields_d, *args, **kwargs):\n",
    "    atomA_coords = fields_d['positions'][:,0]\n",
    "    atomB_coords = fields_d['positions'][:,1]\n",
    "    \n",
    "    dists = np.array([np.array([scidist.euclidean(atomA_coords[i],\n",
    "                                        atomB_coords[i])])\n",
    "                      for i in range(atomA_coords.shape[0])\n",
    "                     ])\n",
    "    return dists\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "wepy1 = WepyHDF5(outputs_dir / 'results_run1.wepy.h5', mode='r+')\n",
    "with wepy1:\n",
    "\n",
    "    # compute the observable with the function \n",
    "    # and automatically saving it as an extra trajectory field\n",
    "    obs = wepy1.compute_observable(pair_dist_obs, \n",
    "                                   ['positions'],\n",
    "                                   (),\n",
    "                                   save_to_hdf5='pair_dist',\n",
    "                                   return_results=True\n",
    "                                  )"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "When we run `compute_observable` it both returns the values and saves them into the HDF5 file. Depending on your workflow you may favor one over the other. In the end having the observables saved in the same HDF5 file makes indexing them easier and allows for some fancy queries when you rearrange the data into networks and trees.\n",
    "\n",
    "We can see what the shape of this data is and that it matches the number of walkers (4) and cycles (100) we ran the simulation with.\n",
    "\n",
    "We can also see that the computed feature is a 1-D feature vector. We retain the rank of a vector rather than a scalar because in most machine learning pipelines a vector is expected. Even if in this case its only length one."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 8,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [

     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",

      "number of walkers: 4\n",
      "number of cycles: 100\n",
      "feature vector shape: (1,)\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "print(\"number of walkers:\", len(obs))\n",
    "print(\"number of cycles:\", obs[0].shape[0])\n",
    "print(\"feature vector shape:\", obs[0].shape[1:])"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Clustering Simulation Samples\n",
    "\n",
    "For a larger dataset clustering can be significantly more involved as it will likely need to be done either using special clustering algorithms (like the `KCenters` algorithm implemented in `MSMBuilder`) and you will probably want to partition your data into training and test sets to validate your model.\n",
    "\n",
    "For our purposes here we will just use a simple fast clustering method from `sklearn`, i.e. the `MiniBatchKMeans` algorithm just so you can appreciate the mechanism and so we have some macrostate labels to use for the later analyses.\n",
    "\n",
    "First we have to get our data as a uniform array of feature vectors which is simple as concatenating the features for each walker trajectory together:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 9,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "(400, 1)\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "with wepy1:\n",
    "    features = np.concatenate([wepy1.get_traj_field(0, i, 'observables/pair_dist')\n",
    "                               for i in range(wepy1.num_run_trajs(0))])\n",
    "    \n",
    "print(features.shape)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Then we can choose our classifier hyperparameters and train it:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 10,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "(400,)\n",
      "[3 1 3 1 1 2 0 2 0 3]\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "from sklearn.cluster import MiniBatchKMeans\n",
    "\n",
    "clf = MiniBatchKMeans(n_clusters=4,\n",
    "                      batch_size=10,\n",
    "                      random_state=1)\n",
    "clf.fit(features)\n",
    "print(clf.labels_.shape)\n",
    "print(clf.labels_[0:10])"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Once we have the trained classifier and we don't have a test set, we can just use the already determined labels for the feature vectors and then assign this to the simulation dataset as it's own observable. To do this we just need to destructure the feature set back into trajectory shapes and use the `add_observable` method on our `WepyHDF5` dataset:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 11,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "observables shape: 4 100\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "with wepy1:\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # destructure the features\n",
    "    obs_trajs = []\n",
    "    start_idx = 0\n",
    "    for traj_idx in range(wepy1.num_run_trajs(0)):\n",
    "        num_traj_frames = wepy1.num_traj_frames(0, traj_idx)\n",
    "        \n",
    "        obs_trajs.append(clf.labels_[start_idx : start_idx + num_traj_frames])\n",
    "\n",
    "        start_idx += num_traj_frames\n",
    "        \n",
    "    print(\"observables shape:\", len(obs_trajs), len(obs_trajs[0]))        \n",
    "    \n",
    "    # add it as an observable\n",
    "    wepy1.add_observable('minibatch-kmeans_pair-dist_4_10_1',\n",
    "                        [obs_trajs])"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Thats it for clustering!\n",
    "\n",
    "For now we will leave it as is and do more things with the macrostate networks once we calculate the transition probabilities.\n",
    "\n",
    "Just remember that even though we are dealing with data as nice big chunks that we are even calling \"trajs\" or \"trajectories\" they are not! The name \"trajectory\" is simply a convenient name for a collection of molecular dynamics frames, i.e. a slice of data containing positions, box vectors, and potentially velocities and energies, that is familiar to the community.\n",
    "\n",
    "A single trajectory may be linear for portions where cloning and merging did not occur, but in others the cloned walkers will be swapped in and out along the \"trajectory\".\n",
    "\n",
    "However, if we ran a simulation in which no cloning and merging occurs (say with the `NoResampler`) then the trajectories indeed would be valid continuous trajectories. Strictly speaking nothing in `wepy` enforces this and in reality resamplers are free to mangle the contiguity of each trajectory. That is, never rely on the well-orderdness of trajectories in `WepyHDF5` runs! \n",
    "\n",
    "The following sections show the correct approach and how to extract contiguous trajectories from walker trees."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "slideshow": {
     "slide_type": "slide"
    }
   },
   "source": [
    "### Computing Macrostate Transition Counts & Probabilities\n",
    "\n",
    "Now that we have computed the observables and clustered them we can compute the transitions between those macrostates. The first step is a purely mechanical process and is just book-keeping about where and when walkers were cloned and merged. You can think of it as just making the family lineage. During the simulation the individual clones and merges are recorded as distinct events, like individual facts. Now we have to go back through this and assemble it into a tree-like data structure.\n",
    "\n",
    "In the second revision of this workflow we will show a higher-level way to do this, but which also makes use of multiple branching simulations. For now we do it the semi-manual way of transforming the \"resampling records\" to a \"resampling panel\" (the `run_resampling_panel` method) and then condensing this to a \"net parent table\" (the `parent_panel` function). Finally we add a mask to this table to account for any walkers that warped through boundary conditions (the `parent_table_discontinuities`). This is necessary for getting transition probabilities correctly since movement through a boundary acts like a probability sink and doesn't represent a physical transition.\n",
    "\n",
    "The `resampler.DECISION` and `UnbindingBC` classes are simply the ones we used in the simulations above. These classes contain methods that allow for proper accounting to be done. The `resampler.DECISION` is just `MultiCloneMergeDecision`."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 32,
   "metadata": {
    "slideshow": {
     "slide_type": "-"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from wepy.analysis.parents import (\n",
    "    parent_panel, \n",
    "    net_parent_table, \n",
    "    parent_table_discontinuities,\n",
    ")\n",
    "\n",
    "with wepy1:\n",
    "    # make a parent matrix from the hdf5 resampling records for run 0\n",
    "    resampling_panel = wepy1.run_resampling_panel(0)\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # get the warping records\n",
    "    warping_records = wepy1.warping_records([0])\n",
    "    \n",
    "parent_panel = parent_panel(\n",
    "    resampler.DECISION, \n",
    "    resampling_panel)\n",
    "\n",
    "parent_table = net_parent_table(parent_panel)\n",
    "\n",
    "parent_table_discs = parent_table_discontinuities(\n",
    "    UnbindingBC,\n",
    "    parent_table, \n",
    "    warping_records\n",
    ")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "#### Side Notes on Lineages and Continuous Trajectories\n",
    "\n",
    "Now that we have the entire table (which represents the walker tree) we can find contiguous trajectories from it. One way to do this is via the `ancestors` function which works on the parent table. We just need to choose a walker at a certain point of time and it will retrieve the entire history of this walker up until that point.\n",
    "\n",
    "In this example I picked one of the walkers at the end of the simulation and showed the first few entries from the resulting \"trace\". Traces in `wepy` are essentially collections of complex indices on the runs, trajectories, and frames (and also *contigs* which will be discussed later) in the data. Because these traces are untyped it can sometimes be confusing as to what the indices are. Be sure to pay close attention to the documentation which should tell you. There are also some disambiguations in the glossary as to the different types of traces.\n",
    "\n",
    "Also pay attention to the fact that we are using the `parent_table`, not `parent_table_discs`. A discontinuous warp breaks a lineage from the `ancestors` function."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 33,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "[(3, 0), (3, 1), (3, 2)]\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "from wepy.analysis.parents import ancestors\n",
    "\n",
    "lineage_trace = ancestors(parent_table,\n",
    "                          100,\n",
    "                          3\n",
    "                         )\n",
    "\n",
    "print(lineage_trace[0:3])"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "In this trace the tuples are complex indices where the values are: `traj_idx`, `cycle_idx`. Which uniquely identifies a walker at a single point in time relative to the parent table. Because the parent table was created straight from run 0 these indices are valid for that run.\n",
    "\n",
    "Using this information we can extract the fields of these walkers as a collection of arrays. For this kind of trace we use the `get_run_trace_fields` since we only are concerned with a single run. Here we are getting the weights of the walkers and the pair distance which calculated earlier.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 34,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "weights:\n",
      "[[0.25]\n",
      " [0.25]\n",
      " [0.25]]\n",
      "LJ-pair distance:\n",
      "[[0.36995744]\n",
      " [0.39919709]\n",
      " [0.37443133]]\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "with wepy1:\n",
    "    lineage_fields = wepy1.get_run_trace_fields(0, \n",
    "                                                lineage_trace[:-1],\n",
    "                                               ['weights',\n",
    "                                               'observables/pair_dist'])\n",
    "print(\"weights:\")\n",
    "print(lineage_fields['weights'][0:3])\n",
    "print(\"LJ-pair distance:\")\n",
    "print(lineage_fields['observables/pair_dist'][0:3])"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Notice that we are excluding the last entry in the trace. Is this an error? It is not, but sometimes the indexes can be confusing. When trying to debug these kinds of issues, it can be very useful to have these two diagrams handy as a reference to the order of events taking place in the simulation.\n",
    "\n",
    "The first is a schematic that focuses on the generation and inheritance of walker states at an abstract level. In this diagram the colors indicate unique states and the boxes they sit in represent the walker index, which is the trajectory index in a `WepyHDF5` run.\n",
    "\n",
    "This figure is particularly helpful in understanding things like the parent table, especially when combined with boundary conditions. The dot and slash in the boundary condition lines indicate that boundary warping can be continuous or discontinuous. As you can see the slash is a discontinuous even because the purple state is replaced with the original white state. Indicating a source-sink non-equilibrium cycle. The dotted line in the resampling portion indicates that walker 1 was merged into walker 2 (AKA \"squashed\") and donated its weight to it but ending the lineage of it's state."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 35,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<PIL.Image.Image image mode=RGBA size=572x297 at 0x7F777001C050>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 35,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "rescale(walker_history_im, 1.0)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "In this diagram we show the actual flow of data in the `wepy` simulation manager and components."
   ]
  },

   "cell_type": "code",

   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "To explain the wrinkle in the trace indexing above we must consider that the parent table above was generated from all of the resampling records available. Resampling occurs after dynamics is finished, and as the name implies generates no novel samples. And so rather than recording frames twice in the HDF5 before and after sampling we simply record the action of what happens.\n",
    "\n",
    "When we ran the simulation above and returned the walkers from `run_simulation` these walkers were the resampled walkers, but those in the HDF5 are those directly produced by the runner. This way we never lose any sampled data. Even if that walker is subsequently warped or merged away.\n",
    "\n",
    "Because `wepy` is focused on molecular dynamics simulations we even provide a method for generating `mdtraj` trajectories from traces. This is hugely useful for quickly converting to a more common format that can be then read by molecular structure viewers like VMD, PyMOL, or Chimera. This relies on the topology of the molecule also being stored in the HDF5 file (currently this is achieved using a JSON format file). But just know that you never need to rely on this method to get the data you need for this kind of conversion i.e. positions and box vectors."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 37,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "<mdtraj.Trajectory with 100 frames, 2 atoms, 2 residues, and unitcells>\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "with wepy1:\n",
    "    mdj_traj = wepy1.run_trace_to_mdtraj(0, \n",
    "                                         lineage_trace[:-1])\n",
    "print(mdj_traj)\n",
    "# save one of the frames as a PDB as a reference topology\n",
    "mdj_traj[0].save_pdb(str(outputs_dir / 'lj-pair.pdb'))\n",
    "# save the lineage as a DCD trajectory\n",
    "mdj_traj.save_dcd(str(outputs_dir / 'lj-pair_walker_lineage.pdb'))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Also note that these trajectories do not include the actual initial structures that started the simulations. These too can be accessed if you need them via the `initial_walker_fields` and `initial_walkers_to_mdtraj` methods."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "#### Back to calculating Transition Probabilities\n",
    "\n",
    "Now that we have a better idea of the continuity of walker trajectories in our simulation data we can turn our attention back to generating transition probabilities between our labelled macrostates.\n",
    "\n",
    "The simplest way to do this is simply to go through the continuous trajectories and take each pair of states `A -> B`, look at the labels and then tally the macrostate transition counts.\n",
    "\n",
    "Naively it seems our job is done. However, things get complicated when we want to consider lag times over the trajectories. That is recording the macrostate transition between not just `A -> B` but rather the `A -> C` transition given `A -> B -> C`. This is desirable for a number of reasons when computing probabilities using stochastic methods like Markov State Models where we want memoryless transitions.\n",
    "\n",
    "Doing this over trajectory trees is not as trivial. First consider what this lag time of 3 would look like for linear MD."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 38,
   "metadata": {
    "slideshow": {
     "slide_type": "-"
    }

     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }

   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Now consider a branchpoint in a tree of trajectories. We must be very careful not to double count or undercount transitions."

  },

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The algorithm to achieve this has been implemented in the `sliding_window` function which generates traces corresponding to the red segments in the above figures."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 42,
   "metadata": {

   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from wepy.analysis.parents import sliding_window\n",
    "from wepy.analysis.transitions import run_transition_probability_matrix\n",
    "\n",
    "# use the parent matrix to generate the sliding windows\n",
    "windows = list(sliding_window(np.array(parent_table_discs), 10))\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "These window traces can then be combined with cluster labels (as an observable) to produce a transition probability matrix directly. See the `wepy.analysis.transitions` module for other similar functions if you want to control how you are aggregating forward and backward transitions."
   ]
  },
  {

     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# make the transition matrix from the windows\n",
    "with wepy1:\n",
    "    transprob_mat = run_transition_probability_matrix(\n",

    "        \"observables/minibatch-kmeans_pair-dist_4_10_1\",\n",

    "\n",

   ]

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Contig Trees\n",
    "\n",
    "The final step before we can construct a network of macrostates is to combine everything into a `ContigTree` abstract data type. In early prototypes we supported construction of networks from both `ContigTree` and parent-table/transition-matrix. This was cumbersome and confusing and so we consolidated this interface to only use `ContigTree` as it is more general, powerful, and easier to use as a user.\n",
    "\n",
    "If you have fastidiously followed up until this point you may be disappointed to learn that most of these steps are also not exactly needed when using the `ContigTree`. However, these data structures are still used in certain contexts and are useful in helping to understand all the layers of structure.\n",
    "\n",
    "So lets update our original workflow to see where the `ContigTree` fits in."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 45,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [

     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }

   "source": [
    "rescale(CSN_workflow_shortway_im, 1.0)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "As you can see most of those complex intermediary formats are folded into the `ContigTree` representation. The `ContigTre` is a combination of a network data structure (`networkx.DiGraph`) and the `WepyHDF5` data. \n",
    "\n",
    "In this tree each node is a single cycle of a simulation. Thus it can express not only ensembles of walkers cloning and merging but whole simulations of ensembles which are branching. Its like there is a tree inside of a tree. Technically, they are forests as well since there is often multiple roots. This whole tree inside a tree is too much complexity for what we are doing at the moment so we will defer our discussion of it until we need it when analyzing multiple simulations.\n",
    "\n",
    "What we want is to get back to the part where we had a transition probability matrix and combine that with our macrostate labels to make a CSN.\n",
    "\n",
    "So we simply construct the `ContigTree` with our dataset and the classes that describe the cloning & merging and boundary conditions like we did before."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 63,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from wepy.analysis.contig_tree import ContigTree\n",
    "contigtree = ContigTree(wepy1, \n",
    "                         decision_class=resampler.DECISION,\n",
    "                         boundary_condition_class=UnbindingBC,\n",
    "                        )"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 64,

   "outputs": [

   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "What have we done? Well the `ContigTree` has an extensive API for a lot of stuff so lets try to focus in on a few interesting ones before we get to the transition probabilities.\n",
    "\n",
    "One of the main features is a richer set of functions for generating commonly useful continuous trajectories.\n",
    "\n",
    "Here we can get the indices (as unorderd traces) for:\n",
    "\n",
    "- all walkers were warped\n",
    "- all of the final walkers in the simulation\n",
    "- all of the squashed walkers"

   "source": [
    "### Multi-Run Data Analysis\n",
    "So far we have assumed nice contiguous data. This is not so with MD data in general which may be split up into different runs.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "If you've checked out thinking about meta-trees, don't worry. You don't really have to think about it. The benefit is however that if the need ever arises and you have multiple simulations run from a single intermediary checkpoint, you won't have to throw out one or the other continuations"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 47,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {

  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "slideshow": {
     "slide_type": "fragment"
    }
   },
   "source": [
    "We want to be able to get transitions between the original run and all of its continuations without double counting."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "slideshow": {
     "slide_type": "slide"
    }
   },
   "source": [
    "### Contig Tree\n",
    "The contig tree is a tree (technically forest) of continuous simulations. For us the branchings happen when a run is continued multiple times."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 46,
   "metadata": {
    "slideshow": {
     "slide_type": "-"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {

    }
   ],

  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",

    "slideshow": {
     "slide_type": "fragment"
    }

  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "slideshow": {
     "slide_type": "slide"
    }
   },
   "source": [
    "### Storage Implementation: Continuations\n",
    "\n",
    "The only thing that must exist is a specification of the continuations that exist in a `WepyHDF5` file."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "print(\"Runs in this file:\", wepy1.run_idxs)\n",
    "print(\"Continuations using the API method:\\n\", wepy1.continuations)\n",
    "print(\"Where it is actually stored in the HDF5:\\n\", wepy1.h5['_settings/continuations'][:])"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "slideshow": {
     "slide_type": "fragment"
    }
   },
   "source": [
    "Run 1 continues run 0, and run 2 continues run 0.\n",
    "\n",
    "This only works within a single file (but we can do interfile linking)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "slideshow": {
     "slide_type": "slide"
    }
   },
   "source": [
    "### API for interacting with continuations: Contigs\n",
    "\n",
    "A contig is a list of runs that form a contiguous dataset.\n",
    "\n",
    "For the continuation (1,0) the contig is (0,1).\n",
    "\n",
    "Contigs can be any number of runs."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {
    "slideshow": {
     "slide_type": "slide"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "print(\"Contig {} has {} frames\".format([0], wepy1.contig_n_cycles([0])))\n",
    "print(\"Contig {} has {} frames\".format([1], wepy1.contig_n_cycles([1])))\n",
    "print(\"Contig {} has {} frames\".format([2], wepy1.contig_n_cycles([2])))\n",
    "print(\"Contig {} has {} frames\".format([0,1], wepy1.contig_n_cycles([0,1])))\n",
    "print(\"Contig {} has {} frames\".format([0,2], wepy1.contig_n_cycles([0,2])))\n",
    "#wepy1.resampling_records_dataframe([0,1])"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "A *spanning contig* is a contig which goes from a root run (a run that does not continue another run) and a leaf run (a run which is not continued). These can be enumerated:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "spanning_contigs = wepy1.spanning_contigs()\n",
    "print(\"The spanning contigs:\", spanning_contigs)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "slideshow": {
     "slide_type": "slide"
    }
   },
   "source": [
    "#### The Contig Tree Class"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Since we have given it everything it needs to make the parent table from the previous example it can automate it all with the appropriate sliding windows algorithms for multiple runs!"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "slideshow": {
     "slide_type": "slide"
    }
   },
   "source": [
    "### The Macro-State Network Class\n",
    "\n",
    "In order to make a Conformation State Network (CSN) we need to have the transitions (end-points of sliding windows) and the labels of the micro-states (frames of simulations) which can be from clustering or whatever else.\n",
    "\n",
    "Because, a ContigTree can in the most degenerate form be a single run it is the most appropriate inputs for a general macro-state network."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from wepy.analysis.network import MacroStateNetwork\n",
    "\n",
    "random_state_net = MacroStateNetwork(contig_tree, transition_lag_time=3,\n",
    "                                     assg_field_key=\"observables/rand_assg_idx\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Because this object directly wraps the WepyHDF5 file, we have access to all the data including weights, positions, box sizes etc. and so we can perform all kinds of fancy operations on a macrostate basis.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "slideshow": {
     "slide_type": "slide"
    }
   },
   "source": [
    "### Weights/Free Energy of the Macrostates\n",
    "\n",
    "Since we are principally interested in the free energy of macrostates the weights of the macrostates are a canonical example. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# compute the weights of the macrostates and set them as node attributes\n",
    "random_state_net.set_nodes_field('Weight', random_state_net.macrostate_weights())\n",
    "\n",
    "# get the weight of a node\n",
    "print(random_state_net.graph.node[39]['Weight'])"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "slideshow": {
     "slide_type": "slide"
    }
   },
   "source": [
    "### Transition Probabilitiy Matrix\n",
    "\n",
    "To make an actual network we would need the transition probabilities as well, which were calculated with the lag time given when we created the network."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "print(random_state_net.probmat)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "slideshow": {
     "slide_type": "slide"
    }
   },
   "source": [
    "### Updated User Workflow"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "slideshow": {
     "slide_type": "slide"
    }
   },
   "source": [
    "### Synergism with CSNAnalysis\n",
    "\n",
    "This is the assymetric probability matrix. You can calculate interesting things with it related to paths etc. with the `CSNAnalysis` package from here on.\n",
    "\n",
    "The purpose of this class is to calculate transition probabilities and create a direct interface to microstates in the HDF5 from a macrostate perspective."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {
    "slideshow": {
     "slide_type": "fragment"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from csnanalysis.csn import CSN\n",
    "from csnanalysis.matrix import *\n",
    "\n",
    "csn = CSN(random_state_net.countsmat, symmetrize=True)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "slideshow": {
     "slide_type": "slide"
    }
   },
   "source": [
    "### Committor Probabilities\n",
    "\n",
    "Calculate the distance between the two particles:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {
    "slideshow": {
     "slide_type": "fragment"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from scipy.spatial.distance import euclidean\n",
    "\n",
    "dists = []\n",
    "for node_id, field_d in random_state_net.iter_nodes_fields(['positions']).items():\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # just use the positions of the first frame in the cluster\n",
    "    pos_A, pos_B = field_d['positions'][0][0], field_d['positions'][0][1]\n",
    "    \n",
    "    dist = euclidean(pos_A, pos_B)\n",
    "    dists.append(dist)\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "slideshow": {
     "slide_type": "slide"
    }
   },
   "source": [
    "Determine the source and sink basins and compute the committor probabilities:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {
    "slideshow": {
     "slide_type": "-"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "    \n",
    "# the sink basins are those close to the unbinding cutoff\n",
    "sink_basin = [int(i) for i in np.argwhere(np.array(dists) > 2.5)]\n",
    "# the source basins are where they are close together\n",
    "source_basin = [int(i) for i in np.argwhere(np.array(dists) < 0.37)]\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"Number of sink states:\", len(sink_basin))\n",
    "print(\"Number of source states:\", len(source_basin))\n",
    "\n",
    "committor_probabilities = csn.calc_committors([source_basin, sink_basin])\n",
    "committor_probabilities[39]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "slideshow": {
     "slide_type": "slide"
    }
   },
   "source": [
    "### Microstates in the Macrostate\n",
    "\n",
    "The macrostate keeps track of the microstates by a 'trace' which in `wepy` parlance is just a list of indices into the main wepy HDF5 data structure to a specific microstate, i.e. list of (run index, walker index, cycle index) tuples.\n",
    "\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "node8_trace = random_state_net.node_assignments(8)\n",
    "print(node8_trace)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "slideshow": {
     "slide_type": "slide"
    }
   },
   "source": [
    "### Visualizing Microstates\n",
    "\n",
    "This is used to make it very easy to visualize the microstates by allowing export to other trajectory software better supported by viewers like `mdtraj`."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {
    "slideshow": {
     "slide_type": "slide"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# get an mdtraj trajectory object from the microstates in a node\n",
    "node8_traj = random_state_net.state_to_mdtraj(8)\n",
    "node8_traj.superpose(node8_traj)\n",
    "print(\"{} frames in macrostate {}\".format(node8_traj.n_frames, 8))\n",
    "import nglview as nv\n",
    "view = nv.show_mdtraj(node8_traj)\n",
    "view"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "slideshow": {
     "slide_type": "slide"
    }
   },
   "source": [
    "### Linking Runs Together\n",
    "\n",
    "When doing many runs over different jobs and with continuations we found that it would be useful to be able to link them all into a single file and thus not have to worry about different files when doing analysis.\n",
    "\n",
    "Luckily, the HDF5 standard provides a way to do this and is now incorporated into `wepy.hdf5`."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "slideshow": {
     "slide_type": "slide"
    }
   },
   "source": [
    "The main methods we can use to accomplish this are:\n",
    "- `clone` : copy the header information in a file without run data\n",
    "-  `add_continuation` : manually specify a continuation within a file\n",
    "- `link_run` : link a single run from another file, optionally creating a continuation\n",
    "- `link_file_runs` : link all runs from another file, preserving their internal continuations"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "slideshow": {
     "slide_type": "slide"
    }
   },
   "source": [
    "#### Example Datasets"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {
    "slideshow": {
     "slide_type": "-"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "rescale(linking_files_im, 1.0)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {
    "slideshow": {
     "slide_type": "skip"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "wepy2 = WepyHDF5(wepy2_path, mode='r')\n",
    "wepy3 = WepyHDF5(wepy3_path, mode='r')\n",
    "with wepy2:\n",
    "    print(\"File 2 runs:\", wepy2.run_idxs)\n",
    "with wepy3:\n",
    "    print(\"File 3 runs:\", wepy3.run_idxs)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "slideshow": {
     "slide_type": "slide"
    }
   },
   "source": [
    "### Code:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {
    "slideshow": {
     "slide_type": "-"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# now we are going to link them all under one linker file\n",
    "linker_h5_path = osp.join(outputs_dir, \"all_runs.wepy.h5\")\n",
    "with wepy1:\n",
    "    all_wepy = wepy1.clone(linker_h5_path, mode='w')\n",
    "\n",
    "with all_wepy:\n",
    "\n",
    "    # link the whole file for wepy1 to preserve the continuations\n",
    "    wepy1_run_idxs = all_wepy.link_file_runs(wepy1_path)\n",
    "\n",
    "    # do the same for wepy2 just to test it on only one run in a file and\n",
    "    # because it is easier\n",
    "    wepy2_run_idxs = all_wepy.link_file_runs(wepy2_path)\n",
    "\n",
    "    # now we need to link the run from the continuation file for wepy2 and\n",
    "    # add in the continuation records\n",
    "    all_wepy.link_run(wepy3_path, 0, continue_run=wepy2_run_idxs[0])\n",
    "    \n",
    "    print(all_wepy.spanning_contigs())\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {
    "slideshow": {
     "slide_type": "skip"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "all_wepy.open()\n",
    "wepy1.open()\n",
    "wepy2.open()\n",
    "wepy3.open()"
   ]
  },
